        "rubricName": "SEGUE Framework — Communication Skills",
        "content": "## SEGUE Framework — five task-sets of medical-encounter communication\nEach task-set scored holistically out of 5. Total 17/25 (0 task-sets excluded).\n\n## Scorecard\n| Domain | Score |\n| --- | --- |\n| S · Set the stage | 4/5 · Very good |\n| E · Elicit information | 3/5 · Good |\n| G · Give information | 3/5 · Good |\n| U · Understand the patient's perspective | 5/5 · Excellent |\n| E · End the encounter | 2/5 · Fair |\n| **Total** | **17/25** |\n\n### S · Set the stage — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"Hi, Lauren. I am Dr. Rissman. I am the pediatrics resident taking care of Ava today. Um, and I hear you have questions, and I wanna see, um, what I can help most with today.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner greeted the parent by name, introduced themselves with role, and confirmed the reason for the visit by inviting the parent's questions. They repeatedly asked the parent to define what would help most (\"how you feel I can help most\"), which begins agenda-setting collaboratively. What caps this below Excellent is the lack of an explicit agenda structure or sequence (\"here's what I'd like us to cover today\"); the framing stayed open-ended rather than mapping the encounter. Privacy is not assessable in this spoken format.\n- **Recommendations:** After eliciting concerns, briefly outline the plan — e.g., \"Let me answer your immune-system worry first, then walk through what to watch for after, and we'll decide together at the end.\"\n\n### E · Elicit information — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** \"take me through, like, what you're reading about, what you're worried about, and how you feel I can help most\"; \"Can you share with me where you heard, um, we should be waiting for four months?\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner explored the presenting concern well and drew out the psychosocial source of the worry (aunt, online parenting groups), which is a genuine strength — they asked open questions and surfaced where the misinformation originated. They also elicited the parent's prior knowledge and expectations. Gaps hold this at Good: there was no exploration of Ava's own biomedical history (prior reactions, health status), and the learner did not probe how the anxiety was affecting the parent's daily life or decision-making beyond the vaccine question. Listening was active and non-interruptive throughout.\n- **Recommendations:** Add a brief biomedical check — e.g., \"Before we talk vaccines, has Ava had any reactions to anything, or any health concerns since birth?\" — to ground the reassurance in her specific situation.\n\n### G · Give information — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** \"the AAP, or American Academy of Pediatrics, recommends these exact same vaccines... based on studies and research and, um, and really, and evidence\"; \"the risks are really short-term risks, so things like fever, um, or rash, or irritability.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner explained the rationale (national evidence-based schedule, intentional timing), gave clear jargon-light instructions on antipyretics (Tylenol vs. ibuprofen, promised written dosing), and repeatedly paused to check understanding (\"I just shared a lot, so I wanna pause\") and encouraged questions. This is solid, patient-centered delivery. What keeps it at Good rather than higher is that the central worry — the \"immune overload\" question the parent raised three times — was never answered with specific content (e.g., that infants encounter far more antigens daily than any vaccine contains). The learner circled back to \"national recommendations\" and \"short-term risks\" without directly explaining *why* the immune system is not overwhelmed, so the explanation was reassuring but not fully substantive.\n- **Recommendations:** Answer the actual question with a concrete mechanism — e.g., \"A baby's immune system meets thousands of germs every day; the few proteins in these vaccines are a tiny fraction of that, so it isn't overloaded.\"\n\n### U · Understand the patient's perspective — 5/5 · Excellent\n- **Evidence:** \"I hear the worry, um, in your voice, and I also hear how important it is to protect Ava\"; \"my job is not to convince you one way or another, but just to show you the evidence\"; \"other parents sharing those things, that's really powerful... I'm sure that is exactly how they feel.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner consistently named and validated the parent's emotions, explicitly addressed the stated barriers (immune overload, spacing, family advice) without judgment, and honored autonomy rather than pressuring. They validated the aunt/peer-group input as meaningful rather than dismissing it, which preserved trust, and closed by thanking the parent for sharing \"your worries and your hopes.\" The parent's own words — \"I appreciate you not pushing me... you actually listening, and not making me feel silly\" — confirm the empathy landed. This is skillful, fluid, patient-centered work.\n- **Recommendations:** Keep doing this — the non-judgmental validation of the peer-group source, paired with autonomy-preserving framing, is exactly what defuses vaccine hesitancy.\n\n### E · End the encounter — 2/5 · Fair\n- **Evidence:** \"I can write at the end of this... the exact amount that we can give Ava\"; \"Let's go ahead and do it. Thank you so much for your time.\"\n- **Rationale:** There was a partial forward plan — the promised written Tylenol dosing and confirmation to proceed with vaccines today. However, the close was abrupt: the learner did not ask whether the parent had any remaining questions before finishing, did not review next steps in the schedule (four- and six-month visits), and did not discuss concrete follow-up or return precautions beyond fever management (e.g., when a fever *would* warrant a call). The encounter ended on gratitude rather than a structured wrap-up.\n- **Recommendations:** Before closing, add a summary and safety net — e.g., \"So today she'll get her shots; give Tylenol at the dose I'll send if she's uncomfortable; call us if the fever is over X or she seems unwell. Her next set is at four months. Any other questions before we go ahead?\"\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Outstanding relational and empathic skill: the learner named emotions, validated the parent's sources without judgment, preserved autonomy, and elicited the true origin of the worry. The parent moved from hesitancy to informed acceptance largely because of this trust-building, and said so explicitly.\n- **Priority gaps** — The single most important content miss was never directly answering the \"immune overload\" question despite it being raised three times; the reassurance leaned on authority (\"the AAP recommends\") rather than mechanism. The close was also thin — no explicit \"any other questions,\" no review of the four-/six-month schedule, and no clear return precautions.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Directly answer the immune-overload concern with a concrete, understandable mechanism, not just an appeal to guidelines.\n  2. Add a brief biomedical check on Ava (prior reactions, health status) before reassuring.\n  3. Close with a structured wrap-up: summarize the plan, give return precautions for fever, note the next visit, and ask for remaining questions.",
