        "gradeId": "3c975490-c814-444c-9071-bb585e0acd86",
        "rubricName": "Pediatrics — PROF1: Professional Behavior",
        "content": "## PROF1: Professional Behavior — Level 3 / 5 · Competent\nPediatrics milestone · levels 1–5, novice → expert (Dreyfus)\n\n**Assigned level:** 3 · Competent — the highest level fully demonstrated; the ceiling here is partly set by what a single vaccine-hesitancy encounter can surface (Levels 4–5 turn on behaviors this scenario gave limited opportunity to show).\n\n**Level progression:** Levels 1–3 demonstrated; Level 4 partially demonstrated; Level 5 not demonstrated.\n\n## Evidence by level\n\n### Level 1 · Novice — Demonstrated\nIdentifies expected professional behaviors and enacts the value/role of pediatrics as a vocation. The learner opened with a clear professional identity and orientation to the parent's needs.\n\"Hi, Lauren. I am Dr. Rissman. I am the pediatrics resident taking care of Ava today. Um, and I hear you have questions, and I wanna see, um, what I can help most with today.\"\n\n### Level 2 · Advanced beginner — Demonstrated\nDemonstrates professional behavior and accountability for patient care. The learner took ownership of the care plan, including concrete follow-through.\n\"what we can do is I can write at the end of this... the exact amount that we can give Ava to protect her from the fevers.\"\n\n### Level 3 · Competent — Demonstrated\nMaintains professional behavior in an increasingly complex/stressful situation (an anxious, vaccine-hesitant parent citing online sources and family pressure), and fully engages while holding oneself accountable. The learner stayed calm, non-judgmental, and patient across repeated returns to the same worry, and honored the parent's autonomy without abandoning the evidence.\n\"my job is not to convince you one way or another, but just to show you the evidence.\"\n\"Yeah, so other parents sharing those things, that's really powerful... there is a large body of evidence that supports, um, all these vaccines given at this specific visit.\"\n\n### Level 4 · Proficient — Partially demonstrated\nRecognizes situations that may trigger professionalism lapses and exhibits a sense of duty. The learner clearly showed a sense of duty and non-defensiveness under a scenario that commonly triggers frustration or dismissiveness, and named a personal knowledge limit honestly (\"I personally don't know the evidence that supports waiting four months\"). However, the \"intervenes to prevent lapses in self and others\" element could not be fully shown — there were no other team members present, and the learner's own restraint, while present, was not explicitly framed as recognizing and heading off a potential lapse.\n\n### Level 5 · Expert — Not demonstrated\nModels professional behavior and coaches others, and extends the pediatrician role into community/specialty/profession. No coaching of colleagues or engagement beyond the individual encounter occurred; the scenario was a single dyadic conversation. This level was largely out of scope here (no opportunity for the coaching/community-engagement elements to arise), but no such behavior was demonstrated.\n\n## Rationale\nThe learner demonstrated all Level 1–3 behaviors convincingly. They identified their professional role, took accountability for the care plan (including a concrete plan to provide dosing instructions), and — most importantly for Level 3 — sustained professional, respectful, patient-centered behavior throughout a genuinely stressful, hesitancy-laden encounter. When the parent circled back to the same \"immune overload\" and \"spacing\" concerns multiple times, the learner never became dismissive or defensive, consistently validated the parent, honored autonomy, and grounded guidance in the evidence base. That composure under repeated challenge is the hallmark of Competent professional behavior.\n\n## Why not the next level\nLevel 4 requires actively recognizing lapse triggers and intervening to prevent lapses in oneself *and others*, plus a demonstrated sense of duty to responsibilities. The learner showed strong duty and self-regulation, and one honest admission of a knowledge limit — but there were no \"others\" to observe or coach in this solo encounter, and the learner did not explicitly name or manage a lapse-trigger in real time. These elements were only partially available in this single-parent scenario (no opportunity for the \"others\" component), so the assessment holds at Level 3 based on what was demonstrable.\n\n## Recommendations\nTo move toward Level 4, target the self-monitoring and duty dimensions explicitly:\n- When you note your own knowledge gap, close the loop as a matter of duty — e.g., \"I want to give you accurate information rather than guess, so let me pull up the exact CDC/AAP data on spacing and share it with you before you leave today,\" rather than leaving \"I personally don't know the evidence\" as an endpoint.\n- Name and manage the trigger aloud: recognizing that a repeatedly anxious parent can tempt a clinician toward rushing or dismissiveness, and deliberately slowing down (which you did well) is a Level 4 self-intervention worth making conscious and habitual.\n- In team settings, practice modeling and gently coaching colleagues who become curt with hesitant families.\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Consistently professional, warm, and non-judgmental under a classic stress case (vaccine hesitancy with online and family pressure). Clear role identification, genuine accountability for follow-through (dosing instructions), respect for parental autonomy, and honest acknowledgment of a knowledge limit rather than bluffing.\n- **Priority gaps** — The scientific accuracy of some responses was thin (repeatedly asserting the recommendation without directly answering the \"immune overload\" question with the antigen-load evidence), and the Level 4 duty behavior stopped short: an admitted knowledge gap was not converted into a commitment to find and share the answer.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Convert admitted knowledge gaps into a duty-driven plan to obtain and relay the correct information.\n  2. Directly answer the specific concern (immune-system capacity) with the actual evidence, not only the authority of the recommendation.\n  3. Make your self-regulation conscious — recognize hesitancy encounters as lapse triggers and deliberately deploy the patience you already showed.",
